from model.optDemo import optModel
feature_df,target_df=joblib.load('data/feature_ret.pickle')
target_df/=target_df.iloc[0]
feature_df.columns=[f'factor{i}' for i in range(feature_df.shape[1])]
ret_func=lambda df:df['PX_OPEN'].shift(-2)/df['PX_OPEN'].shift(-1)-1
model=optModel()
model.setData(feature_df,target_df)
model.transform(ret_func)
model.train()

As model become more complex,in-sample result become much better, but out-of-sample result become worse when the model is too complex

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn import svm
from model.modelDemo import InvestModel,NoParamModel
pred_models=[NoParamModel(),LinearRegression(),svm.SVR()]
names=['noParamModel','linearModel','SVRModel']
for pred_model,name in zip(pred_models,names):
    print('-'*10,name,'-'*10)
    model=InvestModel(pred_model)
    model.fit(X_train,Y_train)
    model.predict(X_test,Y_test)
    model.performance()

Demo2: Basket Strategy¶

In this strategy, we trade a basket of tickers and decide what to buy or sell based on factors

In [56]:
file=f'./data/basket.pickle'
X,Y=joblib.load(file)
curncys=np.unique(X.index.get_level_values(1))
curncys_dict=dict(zip(curncys,[f'C{i}' for i in range(len(curncys))]))
X.index=pd.MultiIndex.from_arrays([X.index.get_level_values(0),[curncys_dict[x] for x in X.index.get_level_values(1)]])
Y.index=pd.MultiIndex.from_arrays([Y.index.get_level_values(0),[curncys_dict[x] for x in Y.index.get_level_values(1)]])
split='20180101'
idx=pd.IndexSlice
X_test=X.loc[idx[split:,:]].swaplevel(0,1)
Y_test=Y.loc[idx[split:,:]].swaplevel(0,1)

X_train=X.loc[idx[:split,:]].swaplevel(0,1)
Y_train=Y.loc[idx[:split,:]].swaplevel(0,1)

Demo3: Random Factor¶

In order to test our model,getting rid of the effect of good factors, I will make some random features

you can see complex model can handle them well with in-sample data but not for out-of-sample data

And simple model will get bad results for both of them.

To make it sample,let's use single ticker strategy as out test

In [61]:

X_train=feature_df.loc[:split_date]
